        <!-- Background -->
        <div id="background" style="margin-bottom: 4rem;">
          <h2 style="font-size: 1.875rem; margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">What is Knowledge Islands?</h2>
          <div class="prose-ki">
            <p>Knowledge Islands began as a response to a specific observation: that most tools and methods for managing knowledge treat it as an information problem. Index it better. Search it faster. Summarise it automatically.</p>
            <p>But the problem isn't retrieval. The problem is that knowledge — the kind that changes how you act, that compounds over time, that can be stewarded across a community — is fundamentally different from information. It requires care, interpretation, and governance.</p>
            <p>Knowledge Islands is a conceptual model for exactly that. It draws from Zettelkasten, PARA, and LLM-native personal wikis, and borrows from the Open Knowledge Format — but it frames the challenge differently. Not "how do I organise my notes?" but "how does knowledge live, grow, and endure?"</p>
          </div>
          <blockquote class="accent-gold" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
            <p class="heading-display" style="font-size: 1.1rem; font-style: italic; line-height: 1.6;">"Knowledge Islands treats knowledge not as a filing problem but as a civilisation question — one that spans individuals, communities, and generations."</p>
          </blockquote>
        </div>

        <!-- Three layers -->
        <div id="three-layers" style="margin-bottom: 4rem;">
          <h2 style="font-size: 1.875rem; margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">Information, Knowledge, Wisdom</h2>
          <div class="prose-ki">
            <p>Knowledge Islands distinguishes carefully between three layers — because confusing them is how most knowledge systems fail.</p>
          </div>

          <div style="margin: 2rem 0; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 1rem;">
            <div class="grid-label-row" style="align-items: start; padding: 1.5rem; background: white; border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-lg);">
              <div style="text-align: center; padding-top: 0.25rem;">
                <p class="heading-display" style="font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 0.25rem;">Information</p>
                <p style="font-size: 0.6875rem; color: var(--color-ink-light); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em;">Independent</p>
              </div>
              <div class="prose-ki" style="max-width: none;">
                <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">Organised data — databases, documents, feeds, records. It exists independently of the reader. You could leave the room and the information would remain unchanged. Structure without meaning.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="grid-label-row" style="align-items: start; padding: 1.5rem; background: white; border: 1.5px solid var(--color-teal); border-radius: var(--radius-lg);">
              <div style="text-align: center; padding-top: 0.25rem;">
                <p style="font-family: var(--font-heading); font-size: 1rem; color: var(--color-teal); font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 0.25rem;">Knowledge</p>
                <p style="font-size: 0.6875rem; color: var(--color-ink-light); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em;">Contextual</p>
              </div>
              <div class="prose-ki" style="max-width: none;">
                <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">Information interpreted and applied. It requires you — your context, your connections, your experience. It changes when you do. Two people reading the same document gain different knowledge from it.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="grid-label-row" style="align-items: start; padding: 1.5rem; background: white; border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-lg);">
              <div style="text-align: center; padding-top: 0.25rem;">
                <p style="font-family: var(--font-heading); font-size: 1rem; color: var(--color-forest); font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 0.25rem;">Wisdom</p>
                <p style="font-size: 0.6875rem; color: var(--color-ink-light); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.06em;">Transcendent</p>
              </div>
              <div class="prose-ki" style="max-width: none;">
                <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">Knowledge used well. Distinctly human. It emerges from reflection over time, and it outlives individuals. Wisdom is what institutions carry across generations — when they manage to carry it at all.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="prose-ki">
            <p>The Knowledge Islands cycle transforms information into the conditions for wisdom. That transformation is the point — and it requires deliberate work.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- The Cycle -->
        <div id="cycle" style="margin-bottom: 4rem;">
          <h2 style="font-size: 1.875rem; margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">The Cycle of Knowledge</h2>
          <div class="prose-ki">
            <p>Islands keep themselves alive through a continuous cycle running at different cadences, in parallel. Both <em>informational change</em> (new input arriving) and <em>reflective change</em> (existing knowledge reframed) are necessary.</p>
          </div>

