        <!-- Territories -->
        <div id="territories" style="margin-bottom: 4rem;">
          <h2 style="font-size: 1.875rem; margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">Territories &amp; Archipelagos</h2>
          <div class="prose-ki">
            <p>Knowledge Islands aren't isolated. They relate — and those relationships have structure.</p>
            <p>A <strong>Territory</strong> is islands organised and governed together. One island — the <strong>Principal Island</strong> — holds governance infrastructure for the whole. Others are <strong>Satellites</strong>: separate, with independent boundaries, but governed within the territory.</p>
            <p>An <strong>Archipelago</strong> is a geographic concept — a natural grouping of islands by proximity or shared character. It is distinct from a territory: a territory may contain one archipelago or span several; an archipelago may sit wholly within one territory or straddle two. Geography and governance are orthogonal structures that overlap without being equivalent.</p>
            <p>The unit of governance is always the territory, not the island. The unit of knowledge is always the island, not the territory. This distinction keeps the model scalable without sacrificing sovereignty.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Agents -->
        <div id="agents" style="margin-bottom: 4rem;">
          <h2 style="font-size: 1.875rem; margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">Agents</h2>
          <div class="prose-ki">
            <p>Two kinds of agent operate within Knowledge Islands — and the distinction between them matters enormously.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="grid-2col" style="margin: 1.5rem 0; gap: 1rem;">
            <div style="padding: 1.5rem; background: white; border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-lg);">
              <p class="heading-display" style="font-size: 1rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">Human Agents</p>
              <div class="prose-ki" style="max-width: none;">
                <p style="font-size: 0.9375rem;">Originate meaning. Apply judgment. Hold ratification authority. Interact through interfaces: notes editors, dashboards, conversational AI. The source of what the island is ultimately <em>for</em>.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div style="padding: 1.5rem; background: white; border: 1px solid var(--color-border); border-radius: var(--radius-lg);">
              <p class="heading-display" style="font-size: 1rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem;">Artificial Agents</p>
              <div class="prose-ki" style="max-width: none;">
                <p style="font-size: 0.9375rem;">Extend scale, speed, and recall. Assist with capture, connection, and curation. Operate through structured protocols (MCP). They amplify human capability — but do not replace human judgment.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="prose-ki">
            <p>Both agents participate in the same knowledge cycle. The distinction lies in the source of meaning: artificial agents can process and connect, but they cannot originate the values that determine what knowledge is worth keeping.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Jurisdiction -->
        <div id="jurisdiction" style="margin-bottom: 2rem;">
          <h2 style="font-size: 1.875rem; margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">Jurisdiction &amp; Governance</h2>
          <div class="prose-ki">
            <p>Every island holds authority over its canonical knowledge. That authority — <strong>jurisdiction</strong> — has structure. Three governance patterns exist: Council (shared authority), Single-governor (individual), and Joint-governor (explicit partnership).</p>
            <p>Standing within an island also has levels. A <strong>Visitor</strong> engages informally. A <strong>Citizen</strong> holds full membership and participates in the cycle. A <strong>Council Member</strong> holds ratification authority — the power to make the island's decisions binding.</p>
            <p>These distinctions aren't bureaucratic formality. They are the mechanism by which an island can evolve without losing coherence — and by which knowledge can be trusted by those who rely on it.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

